  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just an academic concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in Milan, I worked with engineers and scientists who often carried the weight of expectations that they should be 'smart' in ways that felt impossible. I remember a young apprentice electrician, a guy my age, who stopped trying to understand complex circuit diagrams because he kept thinking, 'They all know this already—why am I even here?' That's stereotype threat: the fear that your group's perceived limitations will affect your performance. It's not about being 'less capable'—it's about the psychological burden of being labeled. As someone with a lower secondary education, I know that many people in my generation were told they weren't cut out for technical fields. But I also know that when you remove the label, when you focus on the task itself, not the stereotype, people can do amazing things. We should address it by creating environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. In my workshops, I've seen this happen—when we stop measuring success by how fast someone solves a problem and start by asking 'what did you learn?' the confidence comes back. It's not about changing who we are—it's about changing how we see ourselves in the moment. For those struggling, especially with depression, it's crucial to remember that being good at something doesn't have to come from being 'smart'—it's about effort and patience.",
